---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const proofPoints = [
  {
    label: 'Real runtime behavior',
    text: 'Navigation, forms, timers, and script execution come from the engine, not a mocked UI.'
  },
  {
    label: 'Built for actual workflows',
    text: 'Run local examples, follow live pages, and inspect state without leaving one desktop app.'
  },
  {
    label: 'Layered stack integrity',
    text: 'Transport stays separate from the runtime so network constraints can be tested without muddying engine behavior.'
  }
];

---

<Layout>
  <main class="page-shell">
    <header class="hero">
      <div class="hero-copy">
        <p class="kicker">WaveNav Labs</p>
        <h1>A desktop browser for the early mobile web.</h1>
        <p class="lede">
          Waves is a practical WAP/WML browser for exploring, testing, and improving the stack without
          vague emulation or throwaway demos.
        </p>
        <ul class="hero-benefits" aria-label="Core outcomes">
          <li>Load local examples and live decks in one tool.</li>
          <li>Inspect runtime state and transport behavior as you browse.</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="hero-actions">
          <a class="button" href="./simulator/">Open Simulator</a>
          <a class="button button-secondary" href="https://github.com/dills122/wap-labs/tree/main/browser">Browse Browser Source</a>
        </div>
        <ul class="hero-proof" aria-label="Key project qualities">
          {
            proofPoints.map((point) => (
              <li>
                <strong>{point.label}</strong>
                <span>{point.text}</span>
              </li>
            ))
          }
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="hero-stage" aria-label="Waves product screenshots">
        <figure class="stage-card stage-card-primary">
          <img
            src="./waves-local-forms-example.png"
            alt="Waves rendering a WML form example with editable fields and event timeline"
            loading="eager"
          />
          <figcaption>One desktop shell for local decks, live links, form interaction, and runtime inspection.</figcaption>
        </figure>
        <ul class="stage-highlights" aria-label="Product highlights">
          <li><strong>Input model</strong><span>Softkey-style navigation and focused controls.</span></li>
          <li><strong>Session trace</strong><span>State, snapshots, and timeline visibility while browsing.</span></li>
          <li><strong>Network realism</strong><span>Transport boundaries preserved for constrained-flow testing.</span></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </header>

    <section class="content-grid">
      <article class="panel panel-feature panel-span-4">
        <p class="section-tag">Why it exists</p>
        <h2>Most WAP tooling is either inaccurate, unfinished, or painful to work with.</h2>
        <p>
          Waves is meant to be the practical middle ground: close enough to the original platform to
          be worth trusting, but modern enough to support debugging, iteration, and real development work.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="panel panel-span-4">
        <p class="section-tag">Stack</p>
        <h2>Layered by design</h2>
        <ul class="detail-list">
          <li><strong>Gateway</strong><span>Kannel and the surrounding environment for compatibility testing.</span></li>
          <li><strong>Transport</strong><span>WBXML, WSP/WTP behavior, and the fetch rules that sit underneath the browser.</span></li>
          <li><strong>Engine</strong><span>The Rust/WASM runtime that parses WML, handles navigation, and renders cards.</span></li>
          <li><strong>Waves</strong><span>The desktop host that ties everything together into a usable browser experience.</span></li>
        </ul>
      </article>

      <article class="panel panel-span-4">
        <p class="section-tag">What you can do today</p>
        <h2>Use Waves as a browser, not just a harness.</h2>
        <ul class="detail-list capability-list">
          <li><strong>Browse</strong><span>Open local examples and follow linked WML pages in the same session.</span></li>
          <li><strong>Interact</strong><span>Edit fields, move focus, and submit forms through the real runtime.</span></li>
          <li><strong>Inspect</strong><span>Check state, snapshots, and timelines to understand why each transition happened.</span></li>
          <li><strong>Recover</strong><span>Loading and failures stay visible as product states instead of dead ends.</span></li>
        </ul>
      </article>

      <article class="panel panel-span-12">
        <p class="section-tag">What is shipping now</p>
        <h2>Recent work turned core browser flows into day-to-day tooling.</h2>
        <div class="shipping-layout">
          <div class="shipping-summary">
            <p>
              The current build is optimized for real usage loops: open a deck, interact with it,
              inspect what happened, and continue even when startup or network behavior is imperfect.
            </p>
          </div>
          <ul class="shipping-list">
            <li>
              <strong>Faster navigation loops</strong>
              <span>Back/history and follow-link behavior stay stable while you iterate.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Actionable diagnostics</strong>
              <span>Transport and runtime details are visible without attaching extra tooling.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Local and live parity</strong>
              <span>Move between local examples and live pages with the same browser shell.</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Explicit degraded states</strong>
              <span>Loading and network failure conditions are surfaced clearly, not hidden or frozen.</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </article>
    </section>

    <section class="gallery-band">
      <article class="gallery-copy">
        <p class="section-tag">Proof in the product</p>
        <h2>When requests are slow or fail, the browser stays usable and explicit.</h2>
        <p>
          These states are now first-class behavior. You can still inspect, understand, and continue instead
          of guessing whether the shell is broken.
        </p>
      </article>

      <figure class="gallery-shot">
        <img
          src="./waves-network-loading.png"
          alt="Waves waiting for its first network deck render while keeping the interface visible"
        />
        <figcaption>Loading keeps context visible so sessions do not collapse into blank waiting.</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <figure class="gallery-shot">
        <img
          src="./waves-network-error.png"
          alt="Waves showing a network error state in the desktop shell"
        />
        <figcaption>Failures are surfaced in-product so you can debug and continue quickly.</figcaption>
      </figure>
    </section>

    <section class="cta-band">
      <div class="cta-copy">
        <p class="section-tag">Next step</p>
        <h2>Try Waves first, then dig into the stack behind it.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="cta-actions">
        <a class="button" href="./simulator/">Open Simulator</a>
        <a class="button button-secondary" href="https://github.com/dills122/wap-labs/tree/main/browser">Browse Browser Source</a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <footer class="footer">
      <p>WaveNav Labs · WAP/WML browser, runtime, and protocol tooling</p>
    </footer>
  </main>
</Layout>
